{
  "texts": [
    "Thinking of intentional agency as a pattern in events does not commit one against a reductionist story about how these patterns are realised; it does not commit one to seeing the capacity to generate these patterns as an essential property of cognitive agents.",
    "Overall, I've argued that an Anscombean account makes a well-motivated and compatible partner to HEC.",
    "I've suggested also that this account offers a way of avoiding an impasse in the HEC debate that turns on the availability of a mark of the cognitive.",
    "In the background of this argument is the idea that thinking about agency in this way helps us avoid a picture of cognition as a potentially mysterious property of certain well-defined regions of space, enclosed behind a 'magic membrane' of sensory afference and motor efference.",
    "By seeing extended cognition as a dynamic formal feature of certain brain-centred causal networks, we avoid both the claim that cognition is a property of something other than the brain and the requirement that all aspects of our genuinely cognitive lives be explained only in terms of brain processes."
  ]
}